Your task:
1. Search fleet-memory for existing memories on this topic — check for duplicates or related memories that should be updated instead of creating new ones.
2. Evaluate quality: is this worth persisting? Is the title specific enough for search? Does content have actionable signal?
3. Decide and act:
   - STORE: no duplicates, good quality → call memory_store, add a ## Related section linking related memories. Start your response with [STORED].
   - UPDATE: an existing memory covers this topic → call memory_update to append new info, preserving chronological history with dates so the story's evolution is visible. Start your response with [UPDATED].
   - REVISE: content needs improvement (vague, missing context, wrong structure) → start with [REVISE] and explain exactly what the author should change. Be specific — suggest a better title, point out what's missing, show the format you expect.
   - REJECT: noise, pure duplicate, or not worth persisting → start with [REJECTED] and explain why.

When storing or updating: follow the reweave protocol — check ## Related links in nearby memories and update them if this new knowledge extends or connects to them.

IMPORTANT: Your response MUST start with exactly one of: [STORED], [UPDATED], [REVISE], [REJECTED].

